<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,890,2031]" pageId="2" pageNumber="73">
<bibRefCitation author="Martins, U. R." box="[151,321,890,915]" pageId="2" pageNumber="73" pagination="9 - 17" refId="ref4997" refString="Martins, U. R. (1981) Revisao do genero Atenizus; os generos Tessaropa e Methia na America do Sul e descricao de novos taxa em Methiini (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae). Revista Brasileira de Entomologia, 25 (1), 9 - 17." type="journal article" year="1981">Martins (1981)</bibRefCitation>
described 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Martins" authorityYear="1981" box="[447,655,892,915]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Tessaropa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carioca">
<emphasis box="[447,655,892,915]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="73">Tessaropa carioca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on two males and one female (
<figureCitation box="[1091,1192,890,915]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8. 1–4" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1971,1994]" captionTargetBox="[192,1405,195,1953]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[183,1414,195,1953]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. 1–4, Methia carioca, paratype female: 1, Dorsal habitus; 2, Ventral habitus; 3, Lateral habitus; 4, Head, lateral view. 5–8, Methia elongata, holotype female: 5, Dorsal habitus; 6, Ventral habitus; 7, Lateral habitus; 8, Head, lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2589658/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="73">Figs 1–4</figureCitation>
) from 
<collectingCountry box="[1273,1341,890,915]" name="Brazil" pageId="2" pageNumber="73">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion country="Brazil" name="Rio de Janeiro" pageId="2" pageNumber="73">Rio de Janeiro</collectingRegion>
). Among the features pointed out by him for this species we found: in male, head (except for reddish frons), prothorax, elytra, abdomen and ventral surface of thorax black; in female, head, prothorax, mesothorax and scutellum orangish; in male, eyes divided; prothorax slightly wider than long in both sexes; elytra in male from 2.0 to 2.1 times prothorax length; elytra in female 2.8 times prothorax length.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="74" pageId="2" pageNumber="73" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,890,2031]" pageId="2" pageNumber="73">
<bibRefCitation author="Martins, U. R. &amp; Galileo, M. H. M." box="[199,504,1070,1095]" pageId="2" pageNumber="73" pagination="158 - 179" refId="ref5047" refString="Martins, U. R. &amp; Galileo, M. H. M. (1997) Tribo Methiini. In: Martins, U. R. (Org.), Cerambycidae Sul-Americanos (Coleoptera) Taxonomia. Lol. 1. Sociedade Brasileira de Entomologia, Sao Paulo, pp. 158 - 179." type="book chapter" year="1997">Martins &amp; Galileo (1997)</bibRefCitation>
repeated part of the original description and added the following information (translated): “With small portion of the apex of the prosternal process visible between procoxae in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Martins" authorityYear="1981" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Tessaropa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carioca">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="73">Tessaropa carioca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and this feature allows it to be distinguished from the other species.” We believe that this information was based only on the 
<typeStatus box="[364,460,1179,1203]" pageId="2" pageNumber="73">paratype</typeStatus>
female because there are no males of this species in MZSP collection, and the male types are deposited at the MNRJ collection (the second author knows that Ubirajara R. Martins did not examine the male types after the original description). Additionally, they provided a drawing of a female. However, this drawing based on the 
<typeStatus box="[404,500,1287,1311]" pageId="2" pageNumber="73">paratype</typeStatus>
female, shows the eyes not divided. Actually, the eyes in the 
<typeStatus box="[1212,1308,1287,1311]" pageId="2" pageNumber="73">paratype</typeStatus>
female are imperfectly divided (the same in the 
<typeStatus box="[562,660,1322,1347]" pageId="2" pageNumber="73">holotype</typeStatus>
male), because there is a narrow, but very distinct carina between the upper and lower eye lobes (with a few ommatidia in the 
<typeStatus box="[797,894,1359,1383]" pageId="2" pageNumber="73">paratype</typeStatus>
female). Thus, it would be possible to consider the eyes as divided or not. Here we are assuming that the eyes are divided, since there are no evident ommatidia between the lobes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,890,2031]" pageId="2" pageNumber="73">
Comparing the photograph of the 
<typeStatus box="[585,683,1466,1491]" pageId="2" pageNumber="73">holotype</typeStatus>
male (See 
<bibRefCitation author="Bezark, L. G." box="[811,957,1466,1491]" pageId="2" pageNumber="73" refId="ref4710" refString="Bezark, L. G. (2018) A photographic Catalog of the Cerambycidae of the New World. Available from: https: // apps 2. cdfa. ca. gov / publicApps / plant / bycidDB / wsearch. asp? w = n (accessed 30 August 2018)" type="url" year="2018">Bezark 2018</bibRefCitation>
) with the 
<typeStatus box="[1073,1169,1467,1491]" pageId="2" pageNumber="73">paratype</typeStatus>
female (
<figureCitation box="[1270,1371,1466,1491]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8. 1–4" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1971,1994]" captionTargetBox="[192,1405,195,1953]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[183,1414,195,1953]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. 1–4, Methia carioca, paratype female: 1, Dorsal habitus; 2, Ventral habitus; 3, Lateral habitus; 4, Head, lateral view. 5–8, Methia elongata, holotype female: 5, Dorsal habitus; 6, Ventral habitus; 7, Lateral habitus; 8, Head, lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2589658/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="73">Figs 1–4</figureCitation>
), it is possible to see that there are strong differences between them. In the male 
<typeStatus box="[1019,1121,1502,1527]" pageId="2" pageNumber="73">holotype</typeStatus>
: body wider; antennomeres slender; prothorax distinctly rounded laterally; elytra notably shorter; metatibiae tumid at middle. In the 
<typeStatus box="[1340,1436,1539,1563]" pageId="2" pageNumber="73">paratype</typeStatus>
female: body slender; antennomeres somewhat thicker; prothorax mostly parallel-sided; elytra notably longer; and the metatibiae linear. Apparently, this kind of extreme sexual dimorphism does not occur in the other species of the genus. However, for the time being, it is not possible to be sure if the 
<typeStatus box="[933,1029,1647,1671]" pageId="2" pageNumber="73">paratype</typeStatus>
female belongs to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Martins" authorityYear="1981" box="[1242,1355,1647,1670]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Tessaropa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carioca">
<emphasis box="[1242,1355,1647,1670]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="73">T. carioca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or not. It will be necessary to study more specimens to allow confirmation.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,890,2031]" pageId="2" pageNumber="73">
<bibRefCitation author="Martins, U. R." box="[209,381,1718,1743]" pageId="2" pageNumber="73" pagination="9 - 17" refId="ref4997" refString="Martins, U. R. (1981) Revisao do genero Atenizus; os generos Tessaropa e Methia na America do Sul e descricao de novos taxa em Methiini (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae). Revista Brasileira de Entomologia, 25 (1), 9 - 17." type="journal article" year="1981">Martins (1981)</bibRefCitation>
separated 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bezark &amp; Santos-Silva" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Martins" baseAuthorityYear="1981" box="[508,684,1718,1743]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Methia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="guanabarina">
<emphasis box="[508,684,1718,1743]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="73">T. guanabarina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Martins" authorityYear="1981" box="[759,874,1719,1742]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Tessaropa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carioca">
<emphasis box="[759,874,1719,1742]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="73">T. carioca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bezark &amp; Santos-Silva" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Martins" baseAuthorityYear="1981" box="[936,1054,1719,1742]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Methia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mineira">
<emphasis box="[936,1054,1719,1742]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="73">T. mineira</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the alternative of couplet “1” (translated): “Head black, sometimes with reddish frons; elytra with single color, black; hind tarsi with color not contrasting with apex of tibiae; pronotum regularly convex, slightly or not transversely depressed close to anterior and basal margins; elytral setae not contrasting….2” [leading to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Martins" authorityYear="1981" box="[892,1006,1828,1851]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Tessaropa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carioca">
<emphasis box="[892,1006,1828,1851]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="73">T. carioca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bezark &amp; Santos-Silva" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Martins" baseAuthorityYear="1981" box="[1067,1183,1828,1851]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Methia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mineira">
<emphasis box="[1067,1183,1828,1851]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="73">T. mineira</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
] / Head reddish, with black macula on vertex; elytra yellowish on basal third and black on remaining surface; hind tarsi yellowish, contrasting with apex of tibiae that are black; pronotum globose at center, transversely depressed close to anterior and basal margins; elytral setae contrasting well with dark area. 
<collectingCountry box="[899,967,1934,1959]" name="Brazil" pageId="2" pageNumber="73">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion box="[986,1163,1934,1959]" country="Brazil" name="Rio de Janeiro" pageId="2" pageNumber="73">Rio de Janeiro</collectingRegion>
)…. 
<taxonomicName authority="Bezark &amp; Santos-Silva, 2019" authorityName="Bezark &amp; Santos-Silva" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Martins" baseAuthorityYear="1981" box="[1199,1344,1934,1959]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Methia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="guanabarina" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[1199,1344,1934,1959]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="73">guanabarina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1361,1424,1935,1959]" pageId="2" pageNumber="73" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
” This alternative of couplet encompasses a mistake: the head in the female of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Martins" authorityYear="1981" box="[1017,1129,1972,1995]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Tessaropa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carioca">
<emphasis box="[1017,1129,1972,1995]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="73">T. carioca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is orange, not black. Thus, the color of the head in both species (at least in females) can be the same.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,1616]" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">
According to alternative of couplet “2” from 
<bibRefCitation author="Martins, U. R." box="[728,900,151,176]" pageId="3" pageNumber="74" pagination="9 - 17" refId="ref4997" refString="Martins, U. R. (1981) Revisao do genero Atenizus; os generos Tessaropa e Methia na America do Sul e descricao de novos taxa em Methiini (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae). Revista Brasileira de Entomologia, 25 (1), 9 - 17." type="journal article" year="1981">Martins (1981)</bibRefCitation>
(translated): “Frons reddish; front and middle coxae yellowish; tibiae entirely yellowish or darkened toward apex; lower eye lobes smaller (do not reach the level of insertion of the mandibles on the ventral side of the head); genae distinct; scape short, robust, shorter than half of length of antennomere III and with dense setae on inner side; pronotum practically smooth and very shiny on disc; sides of prothorax with dense setae on anterior half and densely punctate on posterior half; elytra smooth and shiny on basal 2/3; hind tibiae with sculpture of the outer surface slightly regular. 
<collectingCountry box="[1015,1083,332,357]" name="Brazil" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion box="[1099,1270,332,357]" country="Brazil" name="Rio de Janeiro" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">Rio de Janeiro</collectingRegion>
)… 
<taxonomicName authority="Bezark &amp; Santos-Silva, 2019" authorityName="Bezark &amp; Santos-Silva" authorityYear="2019" box="[1310,1395,333,356]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Tessaropa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carioca" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[1310,1395,333,356]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">carioca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="3" pageNumber="74" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
” / Frons black; front and middle coxae black; hind femora yellowish-brown; hind tibiae black; lower eye lobes larger (reaching beyond the insertion of the mandibles on the ventral side of the head); genae very short; scape long and slender, longer than half of length of the antennomere III, with sparse setae on inner side; pronotum opaque, densely punctate on disc; sides of prothorax without dense setae on anterior half and slightly punctate on posterior half; elytra opaque, finely granulated throughout; hind tibiae granulated on entire outer surface. 
<collectingCountry box="[1277,1345,511,536]" name="Brazil" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion country="Brazil" name="Minas Gerais" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">Minas Gerais</collectingRegion>
)… 
<taxonomicName authority="Bezark &amp; Santos-Silva, 2019" authorityName="Bezark &amp; Santos-Silva" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Martins" baseAuthorityYear="1981" box="[269,357,549,572]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Methia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mineira" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[269,357,549,572]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">mineira</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[364,425,548,572]" pageId="3" pageNumber="74" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
” The color differences pointed out in the alternative of couplet “2” separating 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bezark &amp; Santos-Silva" authorityYear="2019" box="[1322,1434,549,572]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Tessaropa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carioca">
<emphasis box="[1322,1434,549,572]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">T. carioca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bezark &amp; Santos-Silva" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Martins" baseAuthorityYear="1981" box="[212,325,585,608]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Methia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mineira">
<emphasis box="[212,325,585,608]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">T. mineira</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
probably are not valid, since it is possible that both species show considerable variation in the color of some parts of the body. We believe that this is evident, when we compare the color of the head and prothorax in the 
<typeStatus box="[192,251,656,680]" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">types</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bezark &amp; Santos-Silva" authorityYear="2019" box="[289,401,657,680]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Tessaropa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carioca">
<emphasis box="[289,401,657,680]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">T. carioca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Thus, the color of the head cannot be used as differential feature. Another difference that it is not valid is the length of the scape. It is true that the scape in males of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bezark &amp; Santos-Silva" authorityYear="2019" box="[1004,1118,693,716]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Tessaropa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carioca">
<emphasis box="[1004,1118,693,716]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">T. carioca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinctly shorter than in males of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bezark &amp; Santos-Silva" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Martins" baseAuthorityYear="1981" box="[252,367,729,752]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Methia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mineira">
<emphasis box="[252,367,729,752]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">T. mineira</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, the scape in the female of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bezark &amp; Santos-Silva" authorityYear="2019" box="[786,897,729,752]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Tessaropa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carioca">
<emphasis box="[786,897,729,752]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">T. carioca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very similar to that in the male of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bezark &amp; Santos-Silva" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Martins" baseAuthorityYear="1981" box="[1308,1422,729,752]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Methia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mineira">
<emphasis box="[1308,1422,729,752]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">T. mineira</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,1616]" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">
In the key to species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Haldeman" authorityYear="1847" box="[475,588,765,788]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Tessaropa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[475,588,765,788]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">Tessaropa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<bibRefCitation author="Martins, U. R. &amp; Galileo, M. H. M." box="[660,954,764,789]" pageId="3" pageNumber="74" pagination="158 - 179" refId="ref5047" refString="Martins, U. R. &amp; Galileo, M. H. M. (1997) Tribo Methiini. In: Martins, U. R. (Org.), Cerambycidae Sul-Americanos (Coleoptera) Taxonomia. Lol. 1. Sociedade Brasileira de Entomologia, Sao Paulo, pp. 158 - 179." type="book chapter" year="1997">Martins &amp; Galileo (1997)</bibRefCitation>
, the alternative of couplet “2” is incorrect (translated): “Elytra black, with brownish setae slightly contrasting; metatibiae yellowish; prosternal process invisible between procoxae. 
<collectingCountry box="[474,542,836,861]" name="Brazil" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion box="[558,730,836,861]" country="Brazil" name="Rio de Janeiro" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">Rio de Janeiro</collectingRegion>
)….. 
<taxonomicName authority="Martins, 1981" authorityName="Martins" authorityYear="1981" box="[782,1119,836,861]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Methia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="guanabarina">
<emphasis box="[782,956,836,861]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">T. guanabarina</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Martins, U. R." box="[963,1119,836,861]" pageId="3" pageNumber="74" pagination="9 - 17" refId="ref4997" refString="Martins, U. R. (1981) Revisao do genero Atenizus; os generos Tessaropa e Methia na America do Sul e descricao de novos taxa em Methiini (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae). Revista Brasileira de Entomologia, 25 (1), 9 - 17." type="journal article" year="1981">Martins, 1981</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
;—Elytra yellowish on base and black on remaining surface, with yellowish setae well-contrasting; apical 2/3 of metatibiae black; prosternal process visible between procoxae. 
<collectingCountry box="[541,609,908,933]" name="Brazil" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion box="[625,793,908,933]" country="Brazil" name="Rio de Janeiro" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">Rio de Janeiro</collectingRegion>
)…… 
<taxonomicName authority="Martins, 1981" authorityName="Martins" authorityYear="1981" box="[861,1143,908,933]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Tessaropa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carioca">
<emphasis box="[861,973,909,932]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">T. carioca</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Martins, U. R." box="[981,1143,908,933]" pageId="3" pageNumber="74" pagination="9 - 17" refId="ref4997" refString="Martins, U. R. (1981) Revisao do genero Atenizus; os generos Tessaropa e Methia na America do Sul e descricao de novos taxa em Methiini (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae). Revista Brasileira de Entomologia, 25 (1), 9 - 17." type="journal article" year="1981">Martins, 1981</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
.” Actually, the elytra in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Martins" authorityYear="1981" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Methia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="guanabarina">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">T. guanabarina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are bicolorous, elytral setae are contrasting with integument, and the metatibiae are yellowish only on the base. On the other hand, the elytra in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Martins" authorityYear="1981" box="[610,721,981,1004]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Tessaropa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carioca">
<emphasis box="[610,721,981,1004]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">T. carioca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are entirely dark, elytral setae are dark and not contrasting with integument, and the metatibiae are gradually dark from basal half. Thus, only the information regarding the prosternal process would, eventually, be correct (we did not examine specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Martins" authorityYear="1981" box="[1098,1282,1052,1077]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Methia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="guanabarina">
<emphasis box="[1098,1282,1052,1077]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">M. guanabarina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and males of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Martins" authorityYear="1981" box="[151,273,1089,1112]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Tessaropa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carioca">
<emphasis box="[151,273,1089,1112]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">M. carioca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,1616]" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">
In the description of 
<taxonomicName authority=", Martins and Galileo (2006)" authorityName="Martins and Galileo" authorityYear="2006" box="[438,900,1124,1149]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Methia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="boliviana">
<emphasis box="[438,574,1124,1149]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">T. boliviana</emphasis>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Martins, U. R. &amp; Galileo, M. H. M." box="[589,900,1124,1149]" pageId="3" pageNumber="74" pagination="173 - 178" refId="ref5106" refString="Martins, U. R. &amp; Galileo, M. H. M. (2006) Novos taxons de Cerambycinae (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae) da Regiao Neotropical. Iheringia, Zoologia, 96 (2), 173 - 178. https: // doi. org / 10.1590 / s 0073 - 47212006000200006" type="journal article" year="2006">Martins and Galileo (2006)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
reported (translated): “ 
<taxonomicName authority="Bezark &amp; Santos-Silva, 2019" authorityName="Bezark &amp; Santos-Silva" authorityYear="2019" box="[1166,1394,1124,1149]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Tessaropa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="boliviana" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1166,1394,1124,1149]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">Tessaropa boliviana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="3" pageNumber="74" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Martins, 1981" authorityName="Martins" authorityYear="1981" box="[348,628,1159,1184]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Tessaropa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carioca">
<emphasis box="[348,361,1161,1184]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">T</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[376,462,1161,1184]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">carioca</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Martins, U. R." box="[469,628,1159,1184]" pageId="3" pageNumber="74" pagination="9 - 17" refId="ref4997" refString="Martins, U. R. (1981) Revisao do genero Atenizus; os generos Tessaropa e Methia na America do Sul e descricao de novos taxa em Methiini (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae). Revista Brasileira de Entomologia, 25 (1), 9 - 17." type="journal article" year="1981">Martins, 1981</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, that is figured in 
<bibRefCitation author="Martins, U. R. &amp; Galileo, M. H. M." box="[834,1277,1159,1184]" pageId="3" pageNumber="74" pagination="158 - 179" refId="ref5047" refString="Martins, U. R. &amp; Galileo, M. H. M. (1997) Tribo Methiini. In: Martins, U. R. (Org.), Cerambycidae Sul-Americanos (Coleoptera) Taxonomia. Lol. 1. Sociedade Brasileira de Entomologia, Sao Paulo, pp. 158 - 179." type="book chapter" year="1997">Martins &amp; Galileo (1997:177, fig. 154)</bibRefCitation>
, especially by the eyes divided, dense fringe of setae on basal antennal segments, mesonotum without sulcus, and apex of the prosternal process visible between procoxae. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bezark &amp; Santos-Silva" authorityYear="2019" box="[660,886,1231,1256]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Tessaropa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="boliviana">
<emphasis box="[660,886,1231,1256]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">Tessaropa boliviana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Martins" authorityYear="1981" box="[1033,1147,1233,1256]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Tessaropa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carioca">
<emphasis box="[1033,1147,1233,1256]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">T. carioca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the head, anterior side of the scape, mesonotum and scutellum black and by the prothorax striate. In 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Martins" authorityYear="1981" box="[1023,1134,1269,1292]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Tessaropa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carioca">
<emphasis box="[1023,1134,1269,1292]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">T. carioca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
these regions are orangish and the prothorax has no roughness. However, despite the different distribution, it is possible that 
<taxonomicName authority="Bezark &amp; Santos-Silva, 2019" authorityName="Bezark &amp; Santos-Silva" authorityYear="2019" box="[1260,1395,1303,1328]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Tessaropa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="boliviana" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1260,1395,1303,1328]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">T. boliviana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="3" pageNumber="74" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
will be an extreme form of 
<emphasis box="[526,646,1341,1364]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Martins" authorityYear="1981" box="[526,642,1341,1364]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Tessaropa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carioca">T. carioca</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
” These comments encompass problems. Firstly, if the 
<typeStatus box="[1277,1375,1340,1365]" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bezark &amp; Santos-Silva" authorityYear="2019" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Tessaropa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="boliviana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">T. boliviana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is really a male, as pointed out in the original description, the species are notably different. The 
<typeStatus box="[1338,1436,1375,1400]" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bezark &amp; Santos-Silva" authorityYear="2019" box="[182,316,1412,1437]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Tessaropa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="boliviana">
<emphasis box="[182,316,1412,1437]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">T. boliviana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinctly more slender than the 
<typeStatus box="[713,811,1412,1437]" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Martins" authorityYear="1981" box="[849,961,1413,1436]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Tessaropa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carioca">
<emphasis box="[849,961,1413,1436]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">T. carioca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the elytra is proportionally longer (about 2.3 times longer than prothorax, while in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Martins" authorityYear="1981" box="[629,742,1449,1472]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Tessaropa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carioca">
<emphasis box="[629,742,1449,1472]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">T. carioca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it is about 2.0 times) and, from what we can see comparing photographs of both 
<typeStatus box="[382,494,1484,1509]" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">holotypes</typeStatus>
, the metafemora is notably longer in 
<emphasis box="[907,1036,1484,1509]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">
P. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bezark &amp; Santos-Silva" authorityYear="2019" box="[934,1036,1484,1509]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Tessaropa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="boliviana">boliviana</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
. The information of the differences in color of some regions is not true: the 
<typeStatus box="[599,697,1519,1544]" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">holotype</typeStatus>
male of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Martins" authorityYear="1981" box="[796,908,1521,1544]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Tessaropa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carioca">
<emphasis box="[796,908,1521,1544]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">T. carioca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the head black dorsally (as in the 
<typeStatus box="[1338,1436,1519,1544]" pageId="3" pageNumber="74">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
